<br>
This is difficult in my opinion and depends on a raid type, which means it starts to get a little subjective.  Say we progress upto the likes of Kunark Dragons.  Can the raid leader reserve items such as Cloak of Flames or say specific spells or items?  What I agree with is that Raid Leaders are under alot of pressure during the raids trying to co-ordinate things.  I think that they should get double raid points to make-up for this.  Items could become a point of contention.  (Edit - another idea is to give them a bonus based on the % of the total points spent on the raid.  For example a Kael raid may spend 20 points, we could give the raid leader a 10% bonus, so he gets 2 additional points?  This way the raid leader gets a bonus based on success of the raid)<br>
<br>
- Do we want the mercenary aid rule? <br>
<br>
The problem here is again difficult.  If the number of points spent is proportional to the number of mercs. then as the person spending the points you'll want to get the best and tightest group you can, i.e. to minimise points spent and maximise likelihood of success.  This is a problem because you start excluding willing members of SCARAB from joining the raid if they won't make alot of difference.  I really like the idea of being inclusive and allowing everyone to come on raids, no matter what their equipment, level or usefulness.  I've been on raids where I haven't added alot, but I've learnt alot.  My epic raid to CoM didn't need 4 or 5 groups, yet 4 or 5 groups of people came along and I am grateful to everyone who did.  I think that we should just award 1 point to everyone who makes the effort to come to an epic/quest battle and 0 points to the person who is gaining.<br>
<br>
Cheers,<br>
Deslok<br>
